article.headline: Bethune-Cookman 57, North Carolina A&T 52
article.story: DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Jimmy Hudson scored all nine of his points during a five-minute segment in the second half to propel Bethune-Cookman past North Carolina A&T 57-52 on Saturday. The win broke a ten-game losing streak for the Wildcats (3-11, 1-4 Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference). North Carolina A&T (6-10, 2-2), which had won three straight, received a game-high 18 points from Jason Wills. Hudson has a team-leading 13.8 scoring average but was held scoreless the first 25 minutes. He nailed a 3-point shot at 14:52 of the second half to put the Wildcats ahead, 37-36, and gave Bethune-Cookman the lead for good at 12:27, sinking another 3-pointer to make the score, 40-39. A final 3-pointer, with 10:16 to play, provided a six-point lead 45-39, that North Carolina A&T could not overcome. Behind some baskets by Josh Cummings and Aaron Nelson, the Wildcats surged to a nine-point advantage, 54-45, and held off a late North Carolina A&T rally that had sliced the difference to three points, 55-52, with 1:07 to go. Hudson and Josh Cummings each had nine points for Bethune-Cookman, with teammate John Anderson claiming a game-high 12 rebounds.
